        <chunk>
          <text>
            The hostile plants begin withdrawingnot fleeing; it's an organized, coordinated retreat, pulling away from the facility in synchronized stages.

            Velvet asks, "Are they leaving?"

            Florence says, "Temporarilythey're regrouping. Assessing. They'll return with adjusted tactics, but we have time."

            The hostile presence fades. The immediate assault stops. We held.

            And everyone is alive.

            ¶

            Exhausted silence fills the spacenobody knows what to say.

            Runner is injured, Velvet is damaged, Remedy is chemically exhausted. Holloway looks drained from hours of coordination. Even Scout has stopped bouncing and is leaning against my leg.

            Florence says, "Status report. Injuries?"

            Holloway says, "Runner needs medical attentionVelvet has significant damageRemedy is chemically exhausted."

            Florence asks Remedy, "Can you produce healing compounds for Runner?"

            Remedy says, "Not until I regenerate chemical capacitytomorrow at earliest."

            Florence says, "Then we use emergency medical suppliesVelvet, can you maintain a minimal defensive perimeter overnight?"

            Velvet replies, "Yesminimal."

            Florence says, "Good enoughHolloway, organize recovery rotations. Everyone needs rest but someone must remain alert in case they return."

            Holloway starts coordinating recoverystill following Florence's tactical guidance because it makes sense, not because anyone is happy about it.

            I finally move from my pillar, legs cramped from hours of staying still. Scout bounces weaklya tired-but-okay bounce.

            "You okay, Scout?" I ask.

            Scout answers with a tired but okay bounce.

            The facility around us looks like a disaster zonetoxic sludge in patches, rubble from collapsed sections, hostile plant matter withering where it breached our defenses. The outer areas we abandoned are completely destroyedbut we're alive.

            I approach Holloway. "How bad is it?"

            Holloway says, "Badstructural damage is extensive. We'll need major repairs. Resources are lowand they'll attack again."

            "But we held this time," I say.

            "Yes," Holloway says.

            Florence is directing Velvet's minimal barrier positioning, making sure the overnight defense is soundstill coordinating, still tactical.

            No one has thanked her. No one has apologized for doubting her. No one has acknowledged that we'd all be dead without her guidance.

            But everyone followed her orders. Everyone worked together. Everyone survived because of the coordination she provided.

            Runner is being treated with emergency medical supplies. Remedy rests, regenerating chemical capacity. Velvet maintains the thin overnight barrier. Holloway organizes watch rotations.

            Florence wheels to the edge of the defended core and positions herself apart from the groupstill isolated, still not included, despite being central to our survival.
          </text>
