          <text>
            I go over to herScout follows.

            I say, "Thank you."

            Florence's platform shifts slightlyFlorence asks, "For what?"

            I say, "You saved everyonethe tactical coordinationwe'd be dead without you."

            Florence says, "I didn't do it for themI did it for you, because you asked, because you're in danger and I can help."

            I say, "I know, but you still saved everyone."

            Florence says, "They don't see it that waythey see 'we needed Florence and that's unfortunate,' not 'Florence helped us and we're grateful.'"

            She's not wrongI look back at the plants recovering, resting and reorganizing; nobody is looking at Florence, nobody is talking to her.

            I suggest, "Give them time."

            Florence asks, "How much time? They needed me during crisiswhen crisis passes, will they need me then, or will I go back to exile?"

            I don't have a good answer.

            Florence says, "We're not donethe hostile plants will return, probably tomorrow with new tacticswe'll need coordination againthey'll need me againthis isn't over."

            I agree, "Noit's not."

            Florence looks at the damaged facility, the exhausted plants, the fragile defensive perimeter. "Necessity created cooperation, but necessity doesn't create forgiveness," she says.

            I ask, "Does it create a foundation for eventual forgiveness?"

            Florence says, "Maybeif they're willing to build on it. But right now they're just tolerating me because the alternative is death. That's not the same as actually wanting me here."

            Scout bounces, soft with sympathy. They like Florencealways have. For Scout it's simple: Florence helps, therefore Florence is good.

            If only it were that simple for everyone else.

            Holloway approachesthe conversation they've clearly been dreading.

            Holloway says, "Florence, your tactical coordination waseffective. Thank you."

            Florence replies, "You're welcome."

            Awkward silence.

            ¶

            Florence fills the quiet and says, "The hostile plants will likely return tomorrowwe should expect adjusted tacticsthey'll probe for whatever weaknesses they identified today."

            Holloway asks, "What do you recommend?"

            Florence says, "Repair what we can overnightprioritize structural integrity and resource recoveryprepare for an extended siege rather than a quick assaultthey'll try to wear us down."

            Holloway processes this. Holloway asks, "And you'llcontinue coordinating defense?"

            Florence replies, "If you want me to."

            Holloway's fruiting bodies shift uncomfortably. Holloway says finally, "Yeswe need tactical coordination. And you provide it effectively."

            It's honest, at leastnot 'we want you,' not 'we're glad you're here.' Just what is necessary.

            Florence says, "I'll help as long as necessaryfor Kira's sake, if nothing else."

            Holloway says, "Understood."

            Holloway leavesthe conversation done, minimum necessary communication achieved.

            Florence watches them go. "See? Necessary cooperation. Not authentic reconciliation."

            I say, "It's a start."
          </text>
