            Someone asks,
            "Is it? Or is it just temporary ceasefire that ends when crisis ends?"

            I don't know, but I hope it's a start.

            The facility settles into exhausted quiet—watch rotations begin and Velvet maintains the thin barrier. Everyone rests as best they can in a wrecked, dangerous space.

            Scout and I find a clear patch of floor near the core—the moss is damaged but still soft enough to lie on.

            I'm exhausted—physically, emotionally, every kind of tired.

            *But we're alive.*

            Tomorrow—the hostile plants will probably return. Tomorrow—we'll fight again. Tomorrow—we'll need Florence's coordination again.

            And maybe, eventually, the plants will see past their hurt to recognize that Florence's value isn't just tactical thinking—it's that she chose to help despite being exiled—she chose to save people who rejected her—she chose right action over resentment. That matters—even if nobody's ready to acknowledge it yet.

            Scout curls up against me, exhausted and loyal.

            Across the damaged facility, Florence sits alone in her isolated position—still needed, still not wanted, but here anyway.

            Because sometimes doing the right thing is its own reason—even when nobody thanks you for it.
          </text>
